																		becoming disillusioned with SCP Foundation
															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/guilliman" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1196171); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1196171&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204958" alt="Guilliman" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1196171)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/guilliman" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1196171); return false;" >Guilliman</a></span> <span class="odate time_1417154403 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">28 Nov 2014 06:00</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2167744">
									

<p>Okay, first of all, no one here probably knows or cares who I am. That's not important. And doubtless there are people who will disagree with me, I know that. But my perspective on the site is just that it is pretty much turning into the opposite of what I find interesting, and what attracted me to it in the first place.</p>
<p>I'm speaking mainly of the general criteria these days for new SCPs. There are several universally accepted guidelines that I personally disagree with.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>First of all, the &quot;no helpful/useful SCPs&quot; rule. Now I'm not suggesting the Foundation should have a bunch of superheroes, magic weapons, and alien technologies at their beck and call, but there should be at least some objects that can be used productively. I find it hard to believe that, in-universe, so few of these things could be beneficial, or useful. A lot of times it seems that adding drawbacks to them is done just to specifically avoid this. An example of what I'm talking about here is <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-896">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-896</a>. Honestly, this one seems to be a typical &quot;over the top item&quot;, it basically takes what happens in this typical type of game and applies it to real life. Only problem is you can't use it effectively because it screws you over, and even if you try to be smart about using it, it still screws you over anyway for no particular reason, just as a generic &quot;fuck you&quot;. I don't find this kind of thing interesting at all. If it could be used effectively without such drawbacks, it would open up many other story possibilities.</p>
<p>That brings me to my next problem - intertextuality. Cross-referencing different SCPs and SCP concepts is completely discouraged. I know this is to stop people from trying to ride the coattails of more popular SCPs, or making things overexposed, but intertextuality has always been one of my favorite things in fiction. Reading a story about X which leaves some unanswered questions, then reading a (mostly) unrelated story in the same setting, which references X and gives you a new perspective on it, and makes you think &quot;Wow, so that's what it was&quot;, or &quot;I never thought of it that way before&quot;, or &quot;so that's what happened to X&quot;. This is why I enjoy things like the interconnected cosmology of Stephen King's novels, or expansive shared universes like comic books.</p>
<p>I realize it can be hard to do this effectively with multiple authors, but having each SCP written as if it's completely isolated from the others always makes me think &quot;Hey, why don't they try using SCP-X to contain this thing?&quot; Or &quot;Why not try what they did to SCP-Y to deal with this one as well?&quot;. It just harms my suspension of disbelief, because I like everything to be interconnected in some way, to get the real feeling that this is a shared universe, not just a bunch of separate stories linked by similar names and writing style. This is why I like stuff like Lord Blackwood's adventures encountering various other SCPs, or the test logs for different methods of destroying 682, even though lots of people hate that.</p>
<p>Another thing is the double standards between old and new SCPs. Many of the Series 1 SCPs, especially the first few hundred, would never make it past muster today, but they still retain high votes, and in many cases are among the top rated pages on the site. If I write something just as good as a famous early SCP, why does it deserve to get downvoted into oblivion and deleted while the early one stays popular, just because I was a few years late? I understand not wanting blatant copies or ripoffs of pre-existing stuff, but I'm talking about original concepts that just wouldn't be considered good nowadays but be lauded in the past.</p>
<p>Also, a lot of the new articles these days seem to fall into one of two categories:</p>
<p>1. Being not all that interesting, but getting by through the use of a gimmick (different type of format, writing style, etc.) This was cool the first few times they did it, but I really think it is getting overplayed. If you want a gimmick, at least have some substance to go with it.</p>
<p>2. Being just plain weird. This isn't necessarily a bad thing, but it seems that since everyone is pushing the &quot;only original ideas&quot; thing so much, and most ideas are taken already, people start coming up with things that sound like they're out of a mad lib (seriously, the Mad Lib Joke SCP might actually have inspired some of these people). Being just plain wacky will only get you so far, at least in my opinion.</p>
<p>If you don't know what I'm getting at here, let me give you a few examples. Using the &quot;top rated pages this month&quot; feature, I'll give my opinions on what is popular lately.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-649-2568-j">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-649-2568-j</a></p>
<p>I really don't understand why this one is so highly rated. It's nothing but a feghoot - a long build-up for a corny pun at the end. Personally I don't find it funny, and I don't get how it is such a highly rated article.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2662">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2662</a></p>
<p>This one is better, but it's still basically a joke SCP in normal SCP's clothing. The idea of a reluctant Lovecraftian deity is amusing, but is this a serious SCP? It's funnier than the aforementioned J, yet they also try to make it serious and scary at the end, which, IMO, just doesn't work. Honestly it's basically a slightly more serious take on the &quot;Sailor Cthulhu&quot; Joke SCP (<a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2006-j">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2006-j</a>).</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2115">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2115</a></p>
<p>This is another &quot;over the top&quot; item, a dating site that connects to other planets and alternate times/dimensions/etc. instead of just Earth. Certainly some potential for story ideas or clever test logs, but I don't see why it's so popular.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2740">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2740</a></p>
<p>This is the first one of the group that I really like. It is incredibly creepy, atmospheric, all-around excellent. It might be similar to some stuff we already have, but it's just so good that I don't really care. This is the kind of SCP I come to the site to read about.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2505">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2505</a></p>
<p>I don't like this one at all. This is the kind of &quot;gimmick&quot; SCP I was complaining about. Take away the format gimmick, and all you have is 055, except it doesn't affect human memories. Even the gimmick itself doesn't make sense - any random person can choose what class it is, then type in something, and the letters magically become a description of 2505? How is that possible, if the information is not being stored outside of someone's memory somewhere? Is the implication supposed to be that the one reading the article is a researcher who has personally examined the thing, and is writing down what he/she learned? If so, what's the point, if the information will just be deleted anyway, before anyone else can read it? And why would it use the exact same wording each time, if it's a bunch of different people describing it from their memories? Also the tags give information about it, but the tags stay on the page without deleting themselves, further breaking the SoD. This one is a lot of flash and no real substance IMO.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2731">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2731</a></p>
<p>This is the other kind of SCP I complained about, the &quot;wacky for the sake of wackiness&quot; kind. Sure, it's weird. It's original. It makes you go WTF. But (and I stress, this is just my opinion), other than that, there's nothing really compelling about it. I don't find it to be particularly cool, creepy, or otherwise interesting. It's just weird to be weird.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2188">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2188</a></p>
<p>I might just be missing something here, but this one doesn't seem to make that much sense. I mean, it's well-written, it's interesting, it's probably my favorite of the ones I've covered so far next to 2740, but it just doesn't seem like an SCP to me, or it doesn't seem to read like one. It's more like a short story about people and their interactions. There's nothing wrong with that of course, but if that is the kind of thing that's getting popular lately with SCPs, it just tells me that the entire SCP format is becoming so restrictive that people have to write something completely different disguised as an SCP in order to have a good article. That doesn't seem like a good sign.</p>
<p>- <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2062">http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2062</a></p>
<p>I like this one. It's an SCP-affecting SCP, which goes with that intertextuality thing I mentioned before, despite not making explicit references to other SCPs. It's also a bit of a gimmick/implied format screw, but it's suitably mysterious and interesting enough on its own.</p>
<p>Anyway, I guess what I'm trying to say is that the site has just been drifting in a direction that doesn't really seem promising to me, moving away from most of the things I liked about it originally and becoming something a bit too stodgy and restricted for my tastes. Basically, I find myself not all that interested in the Foundation anymore, most new articles aren't to my taste, and I figure I just won't be visiting as often as I used to.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p><em>Edit: collapsed that for you - Crayne</em></p>

