			<div class="content" id="post-content-2167769">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>&quot;No helpful skips&quot; is really only enforced to avoid awful wish fulfillment skips, re: a giant laser sword that can kill 682 or a magical gun that can somehow negate 096. Like most cliches on the list, they're not necessarily bad in and of themselves, they're just incredibly difficult to pull off well, and that's why people tend to reject them. If you can make a good useful skip, then people won't complain.</p>
<p>Read Tales. Like, seriously. You want cross references? You want interconnectedness? You want a different take on existing SCPs? You want to see certain skips interact with other skips? Then go read some damn Tales. Honestly, do you even need a <em>reason</em> to read Tales in the first place? They play a pivotal role in the site and flat out ignoring them is just insulting to those who dedicate time to them.</p>
<p>Complaining about double standards in Series I and II/III is like complaining about how old school NES games are horrible by today's standards. I mean, of course they would, because today's standards weren't around back then and thus when they were released they were judged by old school standards. As Reject put it, most shitty old articles survive due to inertia; they get a substantial amount of upvotes from ye olden days to the point where they're safe from deletion and then it takes an entire legion of downvotes to drag it down. I'm sure if this site survives till Series IV or even V that people will look back on Series II and III and criticize it too. Standards change, and there's really nothing we can do about it. Just adapt and move on.</p>
<p>I agree wholeheartedly on the gimmick point. Style over substance, man.</p>
<p>I don't see why randomness is a bad thing. While I do agree that WTFery by itself shouldn't carry an article, I feel it does have a good place on the site; our articles cover a wide range of emotions, so why can't bewilderment and confusion be one? And I don't really see what you see in terms of the number of random articles being posted; the way you said it made it seem like every other skip being posted is an LOLrandom one, whereas I'd say it's like one out of ten or more.</p>
<p>Humor is subjective. You may have found the pun unfunny but tons of people didn't.</p>
<p>Since when did main list skips have to be entirely serious? 2662 is funny and goofy, yes, but it's not a -J. A -J is a skip where its entire existence in the Foundationverse is the joke, re: Santa, the Kool-Aid Man, the Kirby Vacuum Cleaner, etc. And I'm not exactly sure how it tried to be creepy at the end. Could you quote that particular segment? Because I didn't see it.</p>
<p>I'd say because it's digestible. Most of the higher rated skips have that rating because of their digestibility, i.e how easy they are to process and read. Short and sweet skips with a satisfying concept and a decent execution usually go over very well, even if there's not much actually there, because they're easy to pick up and read. I don't really like it, but eh, that's how the community likes things.</p>
<p>Good ol creep is great, and I did love that skip, but I don't think we should restrict ourselves to that genre of skip only. It stagnates creativity by not allowing skips that cover any other genre to be published and it's gotten to a point where with over 2400 skips written with a majority of them focusing in some way or another on creep that original and satiating creep is nearly impossible to pull off.</p>
<p>I agree with this. It's shiny and cool but at its core it's nothing special. I'm all for gimmicks with substance to them but putting a beautiful ribbon on a pair of socks doesn't make it more appealing.</p>
<p>Yeah it's weird, but I just find the idea of &quot;ice cream hell&quot; extremely interesting and thought provoking. I know what kind of weird articles you're talking about but this doesn't seem like one of those to me.</p>
<p>I really don't think that the reason Kalinin wrote this skip the way he did is due to the constraints of the format. If he wanted to write a Tale instead he would've. I think he wasn't ore exploring the constraints of the format rather than acting as a prisoner to them, testing the limits of how much story he could convey in a clinical scientific document. I see nothing wrong with this, and if anything it's a testament to how we're pushing the limits of what a conventional SCP is, not getting boxed in by a restrictive definition.</p>
<p>Good example of a gimmick with substance, yeah.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<p>We definitely are as a site drifting away from our origins, focusing more on the entire spectrum of emotions and not just horror. Whether you like it or not is up to you. I really don't see how it's becoming more restrictive, though. Either way, if you're not coming back, then I hope you enjoyed your time here and goodbye.</p>
<p><em>And collapsed this too. - Crayne</em></p>

							</div>

