				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(637830); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=637830&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204958" alt="SoullessSingularity" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=637830)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/soullesssingularity" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(637830); return false;" >SoullessSingularity</a></span> <span class="odate time_1417157873 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">28 Nov 2014 06:57</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2167764">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Collapsed&nbsp;For&nbsp;Easy&nbsp;Reading&nbsp;-&nbsp;Click&nbsp;To&nbsp;Read!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Click&nbsp;to&nbsp;Hide!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>That brings me to my next problem - intertextuality. Cross-referencing different SCPs and SCP concepts is completely discouraged.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is not true at all. Cross-references are fine as long as it forges an interesting story with it. If it's just slapped on nilly willy hanky panky jammie slammie, then its just using a literary tool badly.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>This is why I enjoy things like the interconnected cosmology of Stephen King's novels</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Why not read the canons? They are filled with this.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>&quot;Hey, why don't they try using SCP-X to contain this thing?&quot; Or &quot;Why not try what they did to SCP-Y to deal with this one as well?&quot;</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You can just write a tale about this. If it's done compellingly, then sure!</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Many of the Series 1 SCPs, especially the first few hundred, would never make it past muster today, but they still retain high votes, and in many cases are among the top rated pages on the site.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Welcome to a democratic voting system, where the oldest get the most views and therefore the most upvotes. This isn't something that could be solveable without a massive restructuring of who can vote, why, and how.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Personally I don't find it funny, and I don't get how it is such a highly rated article.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That's fine. Not the site's problem. Welcome to a democratic voting system.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>This one is better, but it's still basically a joke SCP in normal SCP's clothing. The idea of a reluctant Lovecraftian deity is amusing, but is this a serious SCP?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>As the author of this article I'm going to go ahead and say: <strong>Yes. This is a serious SCP, with a premise concluding to a logical conclusion given the premise.</strong> You don't like it, that's fine. Welcome to a democratic voting system.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>This one is a lot of flash and no real substance IMO</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Welcome to a democratic voting system, where the vote of the newest newbie is equal to the vote of the admin.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I don't find it to be particularly cool, creepy, or otherwise interesting. It's just weird to be weird.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Welcome to a democratic voting system, where the vote of the newest newbie is equal to the vote of the admin.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Basically, I find myself not all that interested in the Foundation anymore, most new articles aren't to my taste, and I figure I just won't be visiting as often as I used to.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>You're not the first nor will you be the last. People get old. Their tastes will change. They move on, or they don't.</p>
<p>If you want to change, start writing SCPs and critiquing SCPs and really giving people examples (i.e. write SCPs) of your style that you're looking for, and so they will be inspired and also write the kind of things you want to see. Look at canons and tales.</p>
<p>Honestly I'm in the same boat as you a lot of the time. But y'know, this is the structure of the site. To change this to your preferences would require a huge restructuring of the community. If you don't like what the community likes, you decide what to do, whether that is to change with it, leave, or write your own style. There are avenues for you to pursue other than writing a huge post about basically &quot;the site doesn't align with my personal tastes&quot;.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

