					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-poke" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1498671); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1498671&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204958" alt="Dr Poke" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1498671)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-poke" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1498671); return false;" >Dr Poke</a></span> <span class="odate time_1417723248 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 Dec 2014 20:00</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2172374">
									

<p>I agree with a good amount of what you said, Soulless, but Guilliman is absolutely correct about the crossovers. It is discouraged, and I for one am sad to see that. Remember the testing logs of 914 and 682? They were great, <em>because they used other SCPs.</em> Back in my earliest days, I always would read a new article and then envision what it would be like if cross-tested. Something about that just lets authors expand so much more on their idea. For instance, if you have a mind-control collar, it's a cool idea, but there's really nothing to it. But putting it on 682 or 173, now THAT'S interesting. It not only expands on the first SCP, it gives you a better idea of how the other SCP works. And yes, it's true that interconnectivity is very present in tales, but tales are often long, confusing, convoluted, in a series, or including references to shit you've never heard of. Articles, on the other hand, are easy to read, explain properly what's going on, never include any crazy shit written by some occult that seems to be translated directly from ancient Sumerian, and even the longest ones don't take hours to sit through. References in tales can be neat, but references in articles are entirely different. They make you consider all the possibilites and limits of something seemingly simple, and such things are DEFINETELY discouraged. I couldn't say why, but cross-testing is frowned upon and kind of seen as a thing of Series I, and that sucks, because that's one of the first things that kept me here. I don't know if the site's going to shit, but you can't deny that that is basically gone.</p>

							</div>

								
					
