			<div class="content" id="post-content-2167780">
									

<p>Wow, what a post. I'll see what I can do to respond to this. Keep in mind though, that while I'm a mod, I'm still relatively new to the site. I've only been here for the last two years.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">This&nbsp;might&nbsp;be&nbsp;a&nbsp;little&nbsp;disorganized&nbsp;since&nbsp;I'm&nbsp;watching&nbsp;Frozen&nbsp;for&nbsp;the&nbsp;nth&nbsp;time&nbsp;with&nbsp;family&nbsp;atm.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">hide</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<blockquote>
<p>First of all, the &quot;no helpful/useful SCPs&quot; rule.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I think this is true in the sense that people tend to discourage weaponizing or excessively using SCPs, because it's too easy to go the wish-fulfillment OTT item route if the draft seems that way. Also, there's the inherent belief that the Foundation doesn't really know if they can trust items to work the way they do forever&#8212;after all, they're anomalous.</p>
<p>It comes down to whether there's a compelling reason for the SCP to be used. That said, there's also articles where anomalous items are <em>made</em> by the Foundation, specifically for use. For example, <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2332">SCP-2332</a> was made to communicate between parallel universes. (I link my own articles because I feel confident that I've got the interpretation of those down for sure&#8212;I don't want to misrepresent other authors' narrative intentions when using them as examples.)</p>
<blockquote>
<p>It just harms my suspension of disbelief, because I like everything to be interconnected in some way,</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yeah, after some people have approached me about it, I can agree. It <em>is</em> a little tough trying to encourage this though, given different authors have different wishes about their work. I'd like to see more people asking authors about crosslinking, myself, since I think it's fine to crosslink if the link makes sense in-universe and there's authorial permission granted so there's no misinterpretation of the work.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If I write something just as good as a famous early SCP, why does it deserve to get downvoted into oblivion and deleted while the early one stays popular, just because I was a few years late?</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Actually, the Rewrite Team's been trying to work on that. People have been recruited to rewrite some of the older articles to bring them up to current standards, and we have an &quot;article up for review&quot; process that brings attention to some of the older stuff that either hasn't aged well or needs more people to look at it. It's been time-intensive, mainly because a lot of older authors aren't around anymore and getting the manpower (writerpower?) can be an issue. And of course, people do like the classics.</p>
<p>A lot of the old stuff is still there largely as relics of the beginning times, because they're relevant to the site's history. All the same, any Series I articles that fall below threshold are subjected to the same deletion process. The stuff that <em>really</em> doesn't age well either gets wiped off or rewritten. I'm not sure if there's much we can do about the high-rated not-so-great stuff, though. The <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/heritage-collection">Heritage Collection</a> was created to address this, but I'm not sure what else can be done about the quality discrepancy. It <em>does</em> become an issue when people see Series I articles and assume it's still the norm.</p>
<p>There are still things written as an attempt to get to the classic SCP length and simplicity, though. <a href="http://www.scp-wiki.net/scp-2023">SCP-2023</a> was partially written to achieve that sort of feel. Wonder of the anomalous, a sense of something more, but not an overwhelming amount of text.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If you don't know what I'm getting at here, let me give you a few examples.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>The joke thing is understandably confusing, yeah. But when it comes to joke articles, if it's funny, that's all most people need for an upvote. The more people think it's funny or chuckle a bit at it, the more upvotes result.</p>
<p>As for the rest, if you're unsure about what makes them interesting, go to the discussion threads. You can leave a comment there if the responses posted by others aren't enough for you; there's nothing wrong with not liking something that a lot of people like. If people start to talk down to you because they feel you're excessively negative, tell a staff member and we'll sort it out.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>
<blockquote>
<p>Basically, I find myself not all that interested in the Foundation anymore, most new articles aren't to my taste, and I figure I just won't be visiting as often as I used to.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I'm sorry that this happened to you, then. I'm sure you're not alone in this.</p>
<p>I will say that I <em>have</em> had the idea to do a &quot;return to classics&quot; SCP contest sometime when I have the time, though. Maybe you would consider looking the site's way once in awhile, even if not as often? The contest will need judges, after all.</p>
<p>Again, sorry if this seems disjointed. Someone farted during the climax scene at the end of the movie with Anna and Elsa, and I'm still having trouble trying not to laugh. I've seen Frozen so many times but hey, context.</p>
<p>Hope this reply helps a bit or at least clarifies some things. Happy Thanksgiving~</p>

							</div>

								
					
