<p>I'm going to try and put this as succinct as possible. Not to change your mind, but to put certain things in context.</p>
<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+&nbsp;show&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">–&nbsp;hide&nbsp;block</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p><strong>1. On &quot;no helpful/useful SCPs&quot; rule.</strong></p>
<p>There is no such rule. Individual members may downvote <em>any</em> article that proposes or implies the use of a scip to the Foundation's advantage, but most members will downvote <em>badly written</em> scips that are used by the Foundation. All it means is that you need to bring it if you want to use it. So to speak.</p>
<p><strong>2. On intertextuality</strong></p>
<p>The discouragement of cross-referencing or cross-testing SCPs is mostly some kind of weird belief in the minds of members who parrot things they read on the site. <a href="/how-to-write-an-scp">How to Write an SCP</a> explicitly talks about how cross-referencing or cross-testing is <strong>not</strong> discouraged in general, just really hard to do right. Just namedropping or cross-testing for the hell of it will get you downvotes. Doing it right will still get you downvotes because some members have this weird belief that it's a no-no, but it will also get you plenty of upvotes.</p>
<p><strong>3. On double standards between old and new SCPs.</strong></p>
<p>You're not understanding how this works. If you want old and new SCPs treated alike, everyone needs to continually think about all of their votes, and recast them as standards evolve. It's simply not feasible the way this site is set up. The only way to address this would be to have a committee of x people decide the fate of all articles judging each of them according to a strict set of standards, updated as time goes by. And even then, they'd have to continually keep going over the articles.</p>
<p>Of course, old articles still get upvotes even though they don't correspond to modern standards. That's due to a few reasons:</p>
<ol>
<li>Misplaced nostalgia (awww&#8230;look at the cute thing that does a thing, those were the days)</li>
<li>Ignorance of current standards (new members start at 001 or 002 and upvoted pretty much every article on the way up the list.</li>
<li>Divergent personal standards (some members just don't agree with current standards and like older articles better - their prerogative of course)</li>
</ol>
<p>I'm sorry this site is losing its appeal for you. I hope you'll find your way back some day.</p>
</div>
</div>
</div>

