<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">++&nbsp;Hello!&nbsp;You&nbsp;had&nbsp;a&nbsp;lot&nbsp;to&nbsp;say!</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">Boy&nbsp;howdy.</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>&quot;No helpful/useful SCPs.&quot;</p>
<p>&#8230; well, there is <a href="/scp-2722">SCP-2722</a>, which was published a couple days ago. Hardly not helpful. Not the only one, either.</p>
<p>There is also friggin' <a href="/scp-2000">SCP-2000</a>, and every Thaumiel article. True, their only raison d'etre is the use the Foundation makes of them, and so they are considered&#8230; uh, unpleasantly not exploitable, rather more like <em>cheaty?</em> Even hypocritical, I guess. But let's face it, this is the age of Thaumiel.</p>
<p>And, on old and new SCP items, you could call bullshit on the fact that many Series I items are garbage or have shamefully un-clinical tone. That's alright, many users do that already. So what?</p>
<p>Now, let's get to what you consider is becoming excessively frequent these days:</p>
<blockquote>
<p>1. Being not all that interesting, but getting by through the use of a gimmick (different type of format, <span style="text-decoration: underline;">writing style</span> etc.) This was cool the first few times they did it, <span style="text-decoration: underline;">but I really think it is getting overplayed.</span> If you want a gimmick, <span style="text-decoration: underline;">at least have some substance to go with it.</span></p>
</blockquote>
<p>How is writing style a <em>gimmick?</em> I mean, I can see why format screws, additional graphics and or media files or even weird CSS magic can be considered gimmicks, but from there to saying writing style can be a gimmick, pfeh, no. It's an artistic choice, same as the gimmicks, with the difference that writing style fits the story and the author to add to the story and improve on the author's writing capacity, whereas gimmicks can be simply add-ons.</p>
<p>Also, I regret to inform you that this is a multi-media site. We do things that transcend text. If the author wants to add gimmicks, they are free to do so, particularly when they believe the media fits a certain intention on their part. Sometimes, it'll be a hookie part of the article, increasing the interest of the reader on your stuff; that is, exactly the same as certain literary devices, but not relying on your capacity as a writer. Why should we constrain ourselves to text, when there is also sound, image, even video?</p>
<p>And, the &quot;at least some substance&quot; bit assumes that the gimmicks can't be interesting enough on their own. See, the SCP main list is a <em>list</em> (Captain Obvious, I know, bear with me) that allows us to compare a) with b), Series I with Series III, scary with weird; it also allows us to contrast <a href="/scp-087">SCP-087</a> with <a href="/scp-2557">SCP-2557</a>. Would you discard either from the main list? One is a long, scary story mostly based on text and a couple of images; the other one is reinforced by gimmicks but remains perfectly valid with a plain text, and still, the reason it racked so many upvotes was the absolutely inspired use of both, in consonance.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>2. <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Being just plain weird.</span> This isn't necessarily a bad thing, but it seems that since everyone is pushing <span style="text-decoration: underline;">the &quot;only original ideas&quot; thing so much, and most ideas are taken already,</span> people start coming up with things that sound like they're out of a mad lib (seriously, the Mad Lib Joke SCP might actually have inspired some of these people). <span style="text-decoration: underline;">Being just plain wacky will only get you so far, at least in my opinion.</span></p>
</blockquote>
<p>I know this is not the time to be self-pimpy, so I apologize. <a href="/scp-2073">SCP-2073</a>, the last thing I wrote, is more scary than weird, but it is both. It also relies on a gimmick to &quot;reward&quot; the reader. I assume the reason why you mentioned kaktus's excellent <a href="/scp-2740">SCP-2740</a> is because you liked its oppressive, strange atmosphere and emotional push into fear and anguish; even then, Series I is not packed with things like that, I believe.</p>
<p>And, incidentally, most ideas are not even explored. Most tropes are, but tropes can be combined and served into original stories; going the spoopy way is a sure way to get you&#8230; well, not downvoted, not necessarily! Going the spoopy way is a challenge, like everything else. Thing is, we are more interested in motherfriggin' worldbuilding, and strange items, and wonderful anguish related to terrible misfortune instead of jumpscares, gore and &quot;oh, well, we are all gonna die. Again.&quot; Most ideas on this front are still warm in our collective creative writing pool, and we choose to steer clear from them until that same collective pool goes to scares again, if we ever do it. Until then, we can all enjoy reading and writing cool stuff that is weird. If you, the reader, don't, don't worry! You can go back to series I if you want. :)</p>
<p>And lastly, yeah, Soulless got it right up above: This site runs on a democratic fashion. No one person can tip the combined motion of the entire audience. Do not worry, the month our skips are considered too over the top or stupidly weird, we will be giving a thought to scares, no doubt.</p>
</div>
