			<div class="content" id="post-content-2172456">
									

<p>I've largely stayed out of this discussion, because people are free to like the things that they like, and a feeling of unhappiness at the move away from the simpler style of SCP articles is not uncommon these days. It's a legitimate reaction, even if I don't share it.</p>
<p>However, your summation of some the current practices on the wiki is inaccurate.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Nowadays, people jump all over you if you have an idea even similar to something already done.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>This is not anywhere close to being a universal reaction among the membership. In fact, the most common feedback I've seen in the chat when a newer member asks if we have a certain kind of item on the mainlist already is that similarity isn't the problem, the strength of the narrative is. The recent success of multiple tooth-horror related articles within a week of each other in the recent past is a testament to this. I don't find this complaint to be based in the reality of what occurs among site membership.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>And forget trying to do something that isn't completely alien and makes no sense at all. For instance, SCP-334, one of the most well-done articles I've seen to date, was downvoted solely on the basis that it was a cat.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Let me just clarify something before we go any further on this point. You're taking issue with the entire site culture nowadays because Bright downvoted an article in 2010. <em>Really?</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p>And this is by Bright, arguably the single most popular and experienced active member to date.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>I wouldn't even call Bright &quot;active&quot; on the wiki these days. And again, your complaint is based on something that happened <em>four years ago.</em></p>
<blockquote>
<p>It's like people have an attatchment to the older articles, but if someone makes something similar, they automatically hate it.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>That is not the dynamic. At all. Standards have changed, like it or not. People do not downvote because articles are similar to something to came before, they largely downvote because what's being written is not <em>interesting</em> in the current environment. Djoric wrote an article recently that was literally a rewrite of a Series I article and therfore the <em>same exact thing</em>, and it was largely successful. What people largely want now is story, a reason to care about something beyond &quot;thing what does a thing&quot;, because &quot;thing what does a thing&quot; as a trope is pretty much exhausted. We've all seen it now literally a thousand times. People aren't downvoting articles of this nature out of some unthinking, knee-jerk reactionary outlook. They're downvoting because they objectively don't like it.</p>
<p>This is a perfectly fine discussion to have, but let's not base it on things that are either not really true or that make no real sense.</p>

							</div>

								
					
