															</div>
				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-poke" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1498671); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=1498671&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610204958" alt="Dr Poke" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=1498671)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dr-poke" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(1498671); return false;" >Dr Poke</a></span> <span class="odate time_1417729867 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">04 Dec 2014 21:51</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-2172481">
									

<div class="collapsible-block">
<div class="collapsible-block-folded"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">+many&nbsp;things&nbsp;were&nbsp;said</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded" style="display:none">
<div class="collapsible-block-unfolded-link"><a class="collapsible-block-link" href="javascript:;">-close</a></div>
<div class="collapsible-block-content">
<p>Alright, here goes. First off, I'd like to say this to both you and Kalinin, and this post is kind of meant for both of you. I wrote that comment in a bit of a rush due to prior obligations, didn't say all I wanted to say, and came off a little rude. Sorry about that, but now I'll make my points clear.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>A majority of the userbase despises most of those older articles that no longer measure up to our standards.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Maybe so, but they certainly aren't vocal about it. I tend to dwell in the comments section rather than the actual articles on SCPs and tales, and it seems that people on the oldie goldies just spam about how great it is, and that's often including the older members, not just the newbies.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>I do agree that disliking an article solely because it uses a concept that's already been done before is kinda dumb, but if it doesn't execute that concept in a unique or interesting way to distinguish it from the all the other articles that use it, it's justified.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Then clearly you're different from the rest of the crowd. Without using an article from 2010, I give you the example of SCP-2189, an article that is, in my opinion, very well written, especially considering it's a second try. However, it's currently at +8, one reason of which, as stated in the comments, is that it's &quot;basically 217.&quot; But, it's not. It's a completely different idea with only one mechanic remaining the same. Clearly, this site holds a lot of bias against things that have already been done.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>The cat thing with 334 is dumb, though.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Yeah, it was. Cut me some slack, I was rushed and didn't have time to check the date on it.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>Yes, they [tales] seem convoluted and unapproachable at first, but if you actually take the time to read a few, they won't.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Maybe some of them, but even so, that's precisely the point. As a newbie, I tried reading some tales, but they didn't make sense. I didn't understand what was going on at all, or who the characters were, or what the fuck a GOC was, but when I read the articles, I knew what was going on the whole time, and that's one of the things that makes the site so attractive to newbies. And added to that are the cross-testings, something that would get newbies to read other articles and find out what's going on there. So yeah, tales are fine, and some of them you can read without any prior knowledge, but a lot of them are only for people who've <em>already read the articles.</em> The articles are the core of the site, and that's why people stay around. Tales are supposed to just be supplements to add a little bit of narrative to the whole universe. But I'm getting off topic.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>there is no tale on this entire site that takes &quot;hours to read&quot;. Series, maybe, but not individual tales.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Your point being&#8230;? Yeah, the ones that are in series often take hours to read, and that's kind of a problem for a site that focuses on short stories. Now, that's not necessarily a bad thing, but once again, as a newbie, if you just read the tales, this site makes about as much sense as 4chan.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>They're no more confusing or reliant on established canons as a majority of SCP articles are</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Of course they are! The SCP format is literally designed to be read and understood in as short amount of time as necessary. When you're reading an article, you almost always know exactly what's going on, but when you're reading a tale, everything's different. Take when I read the Tales From The Bright Side for the first time. (I hate to use Bright as an example again, but this was actually the first time I read a tale.) I had absolutely no clue who any of the people or skips were. It plopped me right into the middle of this strange universe and expected me to have already read so many other things. And again, this isn't necessarily bad, it's just how the tales are different from the articles. But nobody reads tales first and has any clue what's going on. For another example, take the lolFoundation canon and the tale about King. How in fuck's name would a newbie understand the injoke of King and apples? You'd have to have hung around the site for a long time to be able to get that. And yes, I'll admit that there are some articles that do stuff like that, but,<br />
1. Those articles are rare,<br />
2. I think that they're a step in the wrong direction, and<br />
3. They often are referencing other things on the site, and provide links directly to the source, and I'll say it again: this is one of the things that I loved about the site so much when I first joined.</p>
<blockquote>
<p>If you continue to hold this view you're gonna be missing out on some of the highest quality works on the site.</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Obviously, I didn't make this clear: I don't dislike tales. I like them a lot, in fact. But they are very confusing to someone who just joined that site, and crosslinking between articles is one of the major ways that newbies learn more about the site. If we rely on tales to bring us that, nobody's going to want to stay.</p>
<p>Anyway, I've talked too much already, and at this point I'm not even adressing anyone in particular, so I'll just finish off with this. I agree with Guilliman, and I think maybe we should all consider lowering and heightening our standards a little. I would hate to see more people start leaving the site than joining it.</p>
