			<div class="content" id="post-content-2213094">
									

<p>OMG! I agree with Crayne on something! :-)<br />
I don't see that there is a fear of publishing articles, I see that there are a LOT of people coming online who are writing things that, for lack of a better term, simply aren't ready for prime-time. I wrote several SCPs and a Tale and mainlisted a couple. I had my heart crushed when they were downvoted into oblivion. I mean, I put all this HARD WORK and EFFORT into writing these great ideas! How <em>dare</em> people downvote my great work? Then, I took a step back, looked at what I had written, read more high rated SCPs from II and III, did more critique work and tried again. This time it worked. I think people need to realize that if someone is telling them that there is a problem with what they have written, it's not an attack on them personally, it just means there is a problem with what is written. There's nothing to be afraid of when you publish, but I understand why people are afraid. Writing is a <em>very</em> personal process, you're putting your heart and soul into your words and when people downvote, it feels like they are commenting on you as a person. That being said, it just means we have to pick ourselves up and come back as better writers.</p>

